== PAIN MANAGEMENT FOR MOM

Your body just did something extraordinary. Whether you had a vaginal birth or a cesarean, you are recovering from a significant physical event. Pain is normal. Suffering through it without relief is not required.

=== Vaginal Birth Recovery

Most women who deliver vaginally feel sore for one to three weeks, though it can last longer depending on tearing or episiotomy.

*What to expect:*
- Perineal soreness, especially if you had a tear or stitches
- Swelling and bruising in the vaginal area
- Painful urination for the first few days
- Lochia (postpartum bleeding) that gradually lightens over 2-6 weeks
- Afterpains---uterine cramps that intensify during breastfeeding as your uterus contracts back to size. These can be surprisingly strong, especially with second or subsequent babies.
- Hemorrhoids from pushing

*What helps:*
- _Ice packs:_ Apply to the perineum for 20 minutes on, 20 minutes off during the first 24-48 hours. Many hospitals send you home with instant cold packs. You can also freeze padsicles---maxi pads soaked with witch hazel and aloe, then frozen.
- _Sitz baths:_ Sit in a few inches of warm water for 15-20 minutes, 2-3 times per day. You can buy a sitz bath basin that fits over your toilet. This increases blood flow to the perineum and promotes healing.
- _Peri bottle:_ A squirt bottle filled with warm water to rinse the perineum while you urinate (instead of wiping). This reduces stinging and keeps the area clean. Your hospital will likely give you one---use it every time.
- _Witch hazel pads (Tucks):_ Tuck these between a pad and your perineum for cooling, anti-inflammatory relief. You can also line a pad with several for sustained comfort.
- _Stool softeners:_ Your first postpartum bowel movement can be intimidating. Start a stool softener (like Colace) right away---don't wait until you're already struggling. Drink plenty of water and eat fiber-rich foods.
- _Over-the-counter pain relief:_ Ibuprofen (Advil/Motrin) is generally safe while breastfeeding and helps with both pain and inflammation. Acetaminophen (Tylenol) is also safe. Talk with your provider about what's right for you.
- _Dermoplast spray:_ The blue can (not the red one) provides numbing relief to the perineum. Ask your hospital for one, or buy it at any pharmacy.

=== C-Section Recovery

A cesarean is major abdominal surgery. Recovery takes longer---typically 6-8 weeks for full healing, though most women feel significantly better by 2-3 weeks.

*What to expect:*
- Incision pain that is worst in the first few days and gradually improves
- Difficulty standing up straight, getting out of bed, and lifting anything heavier than your baby
- Gas pain and bloating (your bowels slow down after surgery)
- Numbness or tingling around the incision that can last months
- Lochia (yes, you still bleed even after a C-section)
- Fatigue that may feel more intense due to surgical recovery layered on top of newborn care

*What helps:*
- _Pillow over your incision:_ Hold a pillow firmly against your belly when you cough, sneeze, laugh, or get up. This supports the incision and reduces pain significantly.
- _Roll to get up:_ Don't sit straight up from lying down. Roll onto your side and use your arms to push up. This protects your abdominal muscles and incision.
- _Walk early and often:_ Short, gentle walks (even just around the house) help prevent blood clots, reduce gas pain, and speed recovery. It will hurt. Do it anyway---slowly.
- _Prescribed pain medication:_ Take it on schedule, not just when the pain gets bad. Staying ahead of the pain is easier than trying to catch up. If you're concerned about medication while breastfeeding, talk with your provider---most post-cesarean pain medications are compatible with nursing.
- _Loose, high-waisted clothing:_ Nothing should sit on or rub against your incision. Loose pajama pants, nightgowns, or high-waisted underwear that sits above the incision line.
- _Incision care:_ Keep the incision clean and dry. Watch for signs of infection (redness spreading from the incision, warmth, oozing, foul smell, or fever).

=== When to Call Your Provider About Pain

Some pain is expected. But certain symptoms mean something needs attention:

- Pain that is getting worse instead of better after the first few days
- Fever over 100.4 degrees F
- Heavy bleeding (soaking a pad in an hour or passing clots larger than a golf ball)
- Foul-smelling discharge from the vagina or incision
- Redness, swelling, or warmth spreading from a C-section incision or perineal tear
- Chest pain or difficulty breathing
- Severe headache or vision changes
- Pain, redness, or swelling in one leg (possible blood clot)
- Pain that isn't responding to medication at all

Don't talk yourself out of calling. If something feels wrong, call. Your provider would rather hear from you over a false alarm than miss something that matters.

