== NUTRITION FOR RECOVERY AND BREASTFEEDING

Your body is healing and---if you're breastfeeding---producing food for another human being around the clock. This is not the time to diet, restrict, or skip meals. Good nutrition directly impacts how fast you recover and how well your body can keep up with everything it's doing.

=== Why Nutrition Matters Now

Pregnancy and birth deplete your body's stores of iron, protein, calcium, and key vitamins. Replenishing those stores helps your tissues heal, supports your immune system, stabilizes your energy, and improves your mood. Women who eat well in the postpartum period report better energy and faster recovery.

=== Extra Calories for Breastfeeding

If you're breastfeeding, your body needs roughly 500 extra calories per day to support milk production. That's a substantial amount---about an extra meal or two large snacks. This isn't the time to count calories or cut back. Your body is working hard, and it needs fuel.

Signs you're not eating enough:
- Persistent fatigue beyond normal newborn exhaustion
- Dizziness or lightheadedness
- Feeling weak or shaky
- Noticeable drop in milk supply

=== Hydration Is Critical

Dehydration sneaks up on postpartum women, especially those who are breastfeeding. Breast milk is roughly 88% water. If you're not drinking enough, you'll feel it---headaches, fatigue, decreased supply, and constipation.

*Practical tips:*
- Keep a large water bottle everywhere you sit to nurse. Every time you sit down to feed, drink a full glass.
- Aim for at least 80-100 ounces of water per day. More if you're breastfeeding.
- Electrolyte drinks (Body Armor, Liquid IV, or coconut water) can help, especially if plain water is hard to get excited about.
- If your urine is dark yellow, you need more water.

=== Easy, Nutritious Meal and Snack Ideas

You need food you can eat one-handed, prep quickly (or not at all), and that's nutrient-dense. Fancy cooking is not happening right now.

*One-handed snacks:*
- Trail mix with nuts, seeds, and dried fruit
- Granola bars or protein bars
- String cheese or cheese sticks
- Apple slices with peanut butter (pre-sliced)
- Hard-boiled eggs (batch prep ahead of time)
- Yogurt cups or drinkable yogurt
- Banana with almond butter
- Hummus and pita or crackers

*Easy meals:*
- Overnight oats (prep the night before---oats also support milk supply)
- Smoothies with fruit, spinach, protein powder, and nut butter
- Rotisserie chicken with pre-washed salad greens
- Freezer meals you prepped before birth (soups, stews, casseroles, burritos)
- Slow cooker meals your partner or a visitor can throw together
- Sandwiches and wraps---nothing wrong with simple
- Rice bowls with pre-cooked grains and whatever protein you have

*Key nutrients to focus on:*
- _Iron:_ Red meat, spinach, lentils, fortified cereals (especially important if you lost blood during delivery)
- _Protein:_ Eggs, chicken, fish, beans, Greek yogurt, nuts
- _Calcium:_ Dairy, fortified plant milk, leafy greens
- _Omega-3s:_ Salmon, sardines, walnuts, chia seeds (supports baby's brain development through breast milk)
- _Fiber:_ Fruits, vegetables, whole grains, beans (helps with postpartum constipation)

Accept every meal someone offers to bring you. Sign up for a meal train if people are offering help. This is one of the most genuinely useful things anyone can do for a new family.

