== LACTATION SUPPORT

Even if breastfeeding seems to be going well in the hospital, schedule an appointment with a lactation professional---a CLC (Certified Lactation Counselor) or ideally an IBCLC (International Board Certified Lactation Consultant)---within the first week or two of being home.

=== Why Schedule Even If Things Seem Fine

Many breastfeeding issues don't show up until days or weeks in. A latch that looks okay to you might actually be shallow, leading to nipple damage, pain, and supply problems down the road. A professional can:

- Assess your latch and positioning with fresh, expert eyes
- Do a weighted feed (weigh baby before and after nursing to see exactly how much milk transferred)
- Check for tongue tie or lip tie that might not have been caught in the hospital
- Catch small problems before they become big ones
- Give you confidence that things are actually going well, if they are

=== This Goes Double for First-Time Moms

If this is your first baby, you have never done this before. That's okay. But breastfeeding is a learned skill for both you and your baby. Having a professional watch you nurse, make small adjustments, and confirm you're on the right track can be the difference between pushing through the hard first weeks successfully and giving up out of frustration because nobody told you that your latch needed a small tweak.

=== How to Find Support

- Ask your OB, midwife, or pediatrician for a referral
- Search the ILCA (International Lactation Consultant Association) directory at ilca.org
- Check if your hospital has an outpatient lactation clinic
- Many IBCLCs offer home visits---worth every penny when you don't want to leave the house with a days-old baby
- Insurance often covers lactation visits under the ACA. Call your insurance and ask.
- Your local WIC office also offers free breastfeeding support

