== SLEEP ARRANGEMENTS AND SAFE CO-SLEEPING

Sleep---or the lack of it---dominates the first weeks. Where your baby sleeps matters for safety, feeding, and your own survival.

=== Room-Sharing Makes Nighttime Feeding Easier

Having your baby sleep in the same room as you---at minimum---makes nighttime feeding dramatically more manageable. When baby is right next to your bed, you can hear their early hunger cues (rooting, lip-smacking, small sounds) and respond before they're fully crying. You don't have to fully wake up, walk down a hall, and back. You can nurse or bottle-feed and settle them quickly. The AAP recommends room-sharing (but not bed-sharing) for at least the first six months.

A bassinet or bedside sleeper right next to your bed is the standard setup. Some bassinets have a side that drops down so you can reach baby without even sitting up.

=== The Bed-Sharing Reality

Here's the honest truth: most parents will bed-share at some point, whether they planned to or not. Exhaustion is that powerful. A breastfeeding mom who hasn't slept in 36 hours will fall asleep while nursing in bed. It happens. Studies suggest that as many as 60-70% of breastfeeding mothers in Western countries bed-share at some point in the first few months.

The AAP and most U.S. health organizations recommend against bed-sharing due to SIDS and suffocation risk. That's the official guidance, and it's based on real data---particularly for certain high-risk situations. We're not dismissing that.

But telling exhausted parents "never do this" without teaching them how to do it safely means that when it inevitably happens---at 3am when you can barely function---you haven't prepared. Falling asleep accidentally in a recliner or on a couch with your baby is far more dangerous than planned bed-sharing with safety precautions. Couches and recliners are the most dangerous sleep surfaces for infants.

=== If You Bed-Share: Know How to Do It Safely

The *Safe Sleep Seven* framework (from La Leche League and supported by research from Dr. James McKenna's Mother-Baby Behavioral Sleep Laboratory at Notre Dame) outlines the conditions under which bed-sharing carries the lowest risk. All seven conditions should be met:

1. *Mom is a nonsmoker.* Smoking---by either parent---significantly increases SIDS risk regardless of sleep arrangement.
2. *Mom is sober.* No alcohol, no drugs (recreational or sedating medications), no anything that impairs your ability to wake and respond to baby.
3. *Mom is breastfeeding.* Breastfeeding mothers naturally adopt a protective "cuddle curl" position and are more responsive to baby's movements and sounds during sleep.
4. *Baby is healthy and full-term.* Premature, low birth weight, or medically fragile babies are at higher risk.
5. *Baby is on their back.* Always place baby on their back to sleep.
6. *Baby is lightly dressed.* No swaddling in an adult bed. Baby's body regulates temperature partly through contact with you.
7. *The sleep surface is safe:*
   - Firm, flat mattress (no waterbeds, no memory foam, no saggy mattresses)
   - No heavy blankets or comforters near baby---use a light sheet or blanket at waist level only
   - No extra pillows near baby
   - No gap between the mattress and headboard or wall where baby could get trapped
   - No other children or pets in the bed

=== The Framework That Matters

Whether you plan to bed-share or not, know this information. Because at some point, in the fog of sleep deprivation, you may find yourself nursing in bed with your eyes closed. If your bed is already set up safely---firm mattress, no heavy blankets, no gaps---that accidental doze-off is much less dangerous. If you fell asleep in a recliner or on a couch with baby on your chest because you were afraid to bring them to bed, the risk is significantly higher.

Preparation isn't permission. It's harm reduction. Know how to do it safely, because it will probably happen.

