== BABY'S NEED TO BE HELD

Your newborn is going to want to be held. Constantly. All the time. Possibly every waking moment and many sleeping moments too. This is not a flaw. This is not you creating bad habits. This is biology.

=== Why Newborns Need So Much Contact

Your baby just spent nine months in a space where they were held continuously. Constant pressure. Constant warmth. Constant sound of your heartbeat. The world outside is enormous, bright, cold, and nothing is touching them. Of course they want to be back in your arms.

Being held is not just emotionally comforting for your baby---it's physiologically regulatory:

- *Temperature:* Your body helps regulate your baby's temperature through skin contact. This is why skin-to-skin works so well.
- *Heart rate and breathing:* Babies' heart rates and breathing patterns stabilize when held against a parent's body. The rhythm of your own heart and lungs provides a template their body syncs to.
- *Stress hormones:* Cortisol (the stress hormone) drops when babies are held. Babies who are left to cry without comfort show elevated cortisol levels.
- *Digestion:* Being held upright after feeds helps with gas and reflux. The gentle motion of being carried supports digestion.

=== You Cannot Spoil a Newborn

This deserves its own heading because you will hear it from someone---a relative, a neighbor, a stranger in the grocery store: "You're going to spoil that baby."

No. You are not. You cannot spoil a newborn. The concept of "spoiling" assumes a baby is manipulating you to get what they want. Newborns are not capable of manipulation. Their brains haven't developed that capacity. When they cry, they need something: food, warmth, comfort, a diaper change, or simply the reassurance that someone is there.

Responding to your baby's needs---picking them up, holding them, comforting them---builds secure attachment. Research consistently shows that babies whose needs are responded to promptly and consistently in infancy actually become *more* independent and secure as they grow, not less.

=== Practical Ways to Hold Baby and Still Function

- *Baby carriers and wraps:* A stretchy wrap (like a Solly or Boba) or a structured carrier lets you hold baby hands-free. Many newborns will sleep for hours in a carrier while you eat, fold laundry, or just move around the house.
- *Take shifts:* If you have a partner, family member, or friend visiting, pass the baby. You don't have to hold baby every minute yourself. Anyone baby is comfortable with can provide the contact they need.
- *Side-lying nursing:* You can nurse lying down, which lets you rest while baby is fed and held.
- *Let the house be messy:* Holding your baby is more important than a clean kitchen. The dishes will wait.

