== OUR TAKE

*Accept help.* Every casserole, every offer to hold the baby while you shower, every load of laundry someone does for you. Say yes.

*Lower your standards.* The house will be messy. You might not shower daily. That's fine.

*Sleep when baby sleeps* is cliche because it's true. At least once a day, nap when baby naps.

*Limit visitors* who aren't helpful. If they're not bringing food or doing dishes, they can wait.

*Hold your baby.* As much as you want. As much as they want. You're not spoiling them. You're building a human who knows they're safe.

*Feed yourself.* You cannot pour from an empty cup. Eat real food, drink water constantly, and don't feel guilty about eating a lot---your body needs it.

*Get lactation help early.* Even if breastfeeding seems fine. A professional set of eyes can catch what you can't see and save you weeks of struggle.

*Know your sleep setup.* Whether you're using a bassinet or bed-sharing, make sure the space is safe. Read the Safe Sleep Seven even if you don't plan to bed-share. Plans change at 3am.

*Partners: step up.* The first two weeks set the tone. Be proactive. Don't wait to be asked. Mom is recovering from a physical event and learning to feed a new human---she needs you in the trenches, not on the sidelines.

*Baby blues vs. PPD:* Baby blues (weepiness, mood swings) should improve within 2 weeks. If you're still struggling---or if you have thoughts of harm---that's postpartum depression and it's treatable. Tell someone. Call your provider. There is no shame in it, and early treatment makes a real difference.

This phase is hard. It's also temporary. You'll find your rhythm.
